## Implementation Flow

<!-- Ordered steps from "start" to "commit". No steps may be skipped.
     Each step should produce a concrete, verifiable artifact. -->

### Step 1: Plan

<!-- Before writing code, write a plan.
     Output: a plan.md file (or inline task breakdown) listing:
     - Every file to create or modify
     - The test to write first (exact code, no pseudocode)
     - The implementation
     - The verification command
     - The commit message -->

### Step 2: Branch

<!-- Create a dedicated branch for the work.
     Convention: type/short-description, e.g. feat/add-user-export
     Command: git checkout -b feat/your-feature -->

### Step 3: Write the Test First (TDD — Non-Negotiable)

<!-- Write a FAILING test before any production code.
     The test must:
     - Test behavior, not implementation details
     - Be runnable immediately (no stubs needed)
     - Fail for the right reason (not a compile error)

     Run: [your test command] and confirm it FAILS. -->

### Step 4: Write Minimum Implementation

<!-- Write only enough code to make the test pass.
     No extra features. No "I'll need this later." -->

### Step 5: Refactor

<!-- Clean up duplication, naming, structure.
     Tests must still pass after every refactor. -->

### Step 6: Verify

<!-- Run the full verification suite before committing:
     - Unit tests: [command]
     - Lint: [command]
     - Build: [command]
     - Any integration checks: [command] -->

### Step 7: Commit

<!-- One task = one commit. Never batch.
     1. Update CHANGELOG.md
     2. Stage specific files (not git add -A)
     3. Commit with message: type(scope): description -->

## Debugging Protocol

<!-- When something breaks, follow this order. Do not skip steps. -->

### 1. Investigate

<!-- Before changing anything, understand the problem.
     - Read the error message fully
     - Find the exact line that throws
     - Identify the call chain -->

### 2. Analyze

<!-- Form a clear problem statement.
     "The error is X, occurring at Y, when Z happens."
     If you cannot state this, keep investigating. -->

### 3. Hypothesize

<!-- List 2-3 possible root causes ranked by likelihood.
     Pick the most likely one. -->

### 4. Implement Fix

<!-- Change the minimum code needed to address the root cause.
     Do NOT refactor unrelated code during a bug fix. -->

### 5. Verify

<!-- Confirm the original error is gone.
     Confirm no regression: run the full test suite. -->

## Review Process

<!-- Two-stage review gates before merging. -->

### Stage 1: Spec Compliance

<!-- Does the implementation satisfy the acceptance criteria?
     Check each AC item. Mark pass/fail explicitly. -->

### Stage 2: Code Quality

<!-- Does the code follow project patterns?
     Checklist:
     - [ ] Error handling follows the project convention
     - [ ] No hardcoded values that should be config
     - [ ] No dead code, no TODOs left behind
     - [ ] Tests cover the happy path and at least one failure path
     - [ ] CHANGELOG.md updated -->

## Completion Checklist

<!-- The definition of "done." All items must be true before closing a task. -->

- [ ] All acceptance criteria pass
- [ ] All existing tests still pass
- [ ] New tests were written (TDD — test written BEFORE implementation)
- [ ] Lint passes with zero errors
- [ ] Build succeeds
- [ ] CHANGELOG.md updated
- [ ] Commit made with clear message
- [ ] No debug code, console.log, or temporary hacks left in
